    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.13.7-8_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">70 CURVE STREET
                        <lb/>
                    WELLESLEY
                        <lb/>
                    MASSACHUSETTS</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>October 12, 1927</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>If I had no better reason &#8212; as I have, several! &#8212; for acceding to your request that I act on your Board of Advisors, I would nevertheless do it in order to remind you all that our country still has a New England. It is still more than a suburb of New York. We still have, besides our memories, Harvard and Yale, Dartmouth and Amherst and Brown, Smith and Mount Holyoke and Wellesley; we still have <hi rend="underline">The Atlantic</hi>; we still have Frost and Woodberry, Alice Brown and Gamaliel Bradford, and this is but the beginning of our cultural roll-call. Don't you think you could admit seven "cultural areas"? and why not include in your plans "an annual travelling summer camp" for young women as well as young men? You will think you have grasped a nettle!</p>
                
                <p>In point of fact, however, I am deeply in sympathy with your purpose and shall be glad to co-operate as I can. St. Louis is an excellent starting-place, for pride in Lindbergh and pity for the victims of the twister have drawn millions of hearts to your city.</p>
                
                <p>And now may I appeal to you personally to make good this autumn the engagement &#8212; which failed for some reason I never understood &#8212; of last autumn? We who are poetry lovers at Wellesley are eager to hear you read from your poems and especially from that splendid <hi rend="underline">Song of the Indian Wars</hi>. We could pay one hundred dollars and your travelling expenses. Couldn't you slip away from the Post Dispatch and run up for such an hour's reading? We would greatly prefer the first or second Tuesday afternoon
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.13.7-8_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">8</fw>
                
                    in November, but if you can't come then but would come later, let me know and we will do our best to tuck that precious hour into our highly crowded and complicated schedule.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Most sincerely yours</salute>
                
                    <signed>Katharine Lee Bates</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
